  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 尹母崔夫人墓誌 幷序
  author: 李穡
  language: lzh
  text: 栗亭尹文貞公爲其子今三司副使龜生擇婦。聞夫人賢。執女工。豐寒盛暑不輟。而又勉其弟。毋墜家聲。文貞曰是足以配吾子矣。以禮聘之。旣至。事尊章盡婦職。嫁其弟撫其女如己出。族屬或飢寒。夫人衣食之。而自甘菜色。文貞之祖先墳墓在錦者七所。三司歲時拜掃。夫人力貧治奠物如式。仁親敬先。蓋天性云。夫人長子曰紹宗。吾門生。乙巳科狀元也。今爲典儀副令藝文應敎。文貞之老于錦也。每見夫人曰。吾孝婦吾孝婦。我家出狀元矣。及文貞卒葬。夫人過哀盡喪禮。洪武辛酉冬十月壬戌。以病歿。年六十五。壬寅。葬于錦之南山。文貞之塋之右。朝之士大夫哭以詩。相其挽者相續。走其弟成均博士會宗請銘。會宗齊衰犯霜雪。予哀之不忍辭。乃書其家世子孫而系以銘。夫人崔氏。孤竹郡人。經德齋生諱峙。其曾祖也。三別抄之叛。逃難漁中不汚。禮賓丞同正諱臣牧。其祖也。隱不仕。人目之曰處士。進士諱英粹。其父也。有詩名早歿。朱溪事審官雙阜監務裴君諱宗衍。其外祖也。廉平字民。孫男女若干人。典儀娶右尹姜昌壽之女。生一女。繼室以判書朴瓊之女。生一男曰匯。博士娶判事鄭仁彦之女。生二男。曰江曰河皆幼。銘曰。爲女執德。爲婦蹈則。爲母有儀。其儀不忒。宜有其子。榮以祿食。生事文貞。死藏其側。山密水長。實惟玄宅。庶其勿訛。保玆石刻。
korean:
  title: 윤모 최부인 묘지 병서
  author: 이색
  language: kor
  text: |-
    율정(栗亭) 윤 문정공(尹文貞公)이 그의 아들 지금 삼사부사(三司副使) 구생(龜生)을 위하여 며느리를 택할 때, 부인이 어질어 여공(女工)을 행하되 추운 겨울이나 더운 여름에도 쉬지 않고 또 그 아우에게 가문의 명성을 떨어뜨리지 말라 한다는 소문을 듣고 문정공이 말하기를, “이 규수가 내 며느리감이다.” 하고는 예로써 맞이하였다. 시집온 뒤에 시부모 섬김에 며느리의 직분을 다하고 시누이를 시집보내며, 그 딸을 기르되 마치 자신의 자식과 같이 돌보았으며, 일가 중에 혹시 굶주리고 춥다면 부인이 의식을 주고 스스로는 주리는 것을 당연히 여겼다. 문정공 조상의 분묘가 금(錦)에 있는 것이 일곱 군데였는데, 삼사(三司)가 세시로 제사하며 부인이 가난함에도 불구하고 전물(典物)을 예식대로 장만하였으니, 어버이를 잘 섬기고 조상에게 공경함은 천성에서 나온 것이다. 부인의 장자 소종(紹宗)은 나의 문생이니, 을사년 과거에서 장원하였으며 지금 전의부령(典儀副令) 예문관응교이다. 문정공이 금(錦)에서 늙을 때, 매양 부인을 보고는, “나의 어진 며느리여, 나의 어진 며느리여, 우리 집에서 장원을 낳았구나.” 하였다. 문정공이 졸하여 장사 지낼 때, 부인이 몹시 슬퍼하며 상례(喪禮)를 다하였다. 홍무(洪武) 신유년 겨울 10월 임술일에 병으로 마치니, 나이 65세였다. 금의 남산(南山) 문정공 묘소 오른편에 장사하였는데 조정의 사대부로서 만사(輓詞)로 곡한 자가 많았다. 그의 아우 성균박사(成均博士) 회종(會宗)을 보내어 명(銘)을 청하니, 회종이 상복을 입고 눈과 서리를 밟으니 내 슬피 여겨 차마 사양을 하지 못하고, 이에 그 가세(家世)와 자손을 쓰고는 명(銘)을 이었다. 부인은 최씨(崔氏)요, 본관은 고죽(孤竹)이다. 경덕재생(經德齋生) 휘 치(峙)는 증조인데, 삼별초가 반란을 일으킬 때 어부 중에 도피하여 더럽히지 않았고, 예빈승동정(禮賓丞同正) 휘 신목(臣牧)은 조부인데, 은둔하여 벼슬하지 않으니 사람들이 처사(處士)라고 지목하였고, 진사 휘 영수(英粹)는 아버지로 시명(詩名)이 있었으나 일찍 돌아가고, 주계사심관 쌍부감무(朱溪事審官雙阜監務) 배군(裵君) 휘 종연(宗衍)은 그 외조로 공평하고 백성을 사랑하였다. 손자와 손녀가 약간 명이 있는데, 전의(典儀)는 우윤(右尹) 강창수(姜昌壽)의 딸에게 장가들어 딸 하나를 낳았고, 판서 박경(朴瓊)의 딸을 계실(繼室)로 삼아 아들 하나를 낳았으니, 이름은 회(匯)이며, 박사는 판사(判事) 정인언(鄭仁彦)의 딸에게 장가들어 아들 둘을 낳았으니, 이름은 강(江)과 하(河)인데 모두 어리다. 명은 다음과 같다.
    딸이 되어 덕을 잡고
    며느리로서는 법도가 있었네
    어머니가 되어 위의가 있으니
    그 위의 그르지 않았소
    의당 아름다운 아들
    영화와 녹으로 봉양하네
    살아서는 문정을 섬기더니
    죽어서는 그 곁에 장사하네
    얽힌 산과 긴 물
    이곳이 실로 현택이요
    거의 잘못되지 않아
    이 새긴 돌이 보전되리
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1310_010_0060&viewSync=OT
english:
  title: Epitaph for the Tomb of Lady Choi, Mother of Yun
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Master Yun Munjong of Yuljung sought a bride for his son, now Vice Minister of the Three Ministries, he heard that this lady possessed virtue—she labored at her needlework through bitter cold and scorching heat without rest, and exhorted her younger brother never to bring shame upon their family name. Master Munjong declared, "This maiden is worthy to be my daughter-in-law," and betrothed her with proper rites.

    Upon her arrival, she fulfilled the duties of a dutiful daughter-in-law, caring for her husband's kin as though they were her own children. When any of the extended family suffered hunger or cold, she clothed and fed them, content herself with simple fare. Though her husband's ancestral graves numbered seven in Keum, and he made seasonal visits to pay respects, she—though poor—prepared the offerings according to proper custom. Her filial reverence and ancestral piety seemed to flow from her very nature.

    Her eldest son, Sojong, was my own student and became the top graduate of the Eulsa examination. He now serves as Vice Director of Ceremonial Rites and Instructor at the Hall of Elegant Literature. When Master Munjong grew old in Keum, he would gaze upon his daughter-in-law and say, "My virtuous daughter-in-law! My virtuous daughter-in-law! Our house has produced a state examiner!"

    When Master Munjong passed away and was laid to rest, the lady mourned deeply and observed all rites of mourning. In the tenth month of the Sinyu year under the Hongwu reign, on the day Imseul, she died of illness at the age of sixty-five. She was buried on the southern mountain of Keum, to the right of Master Munjong's tomb. The officials and gentlemen of the court wept in verse, and elegies followed one after another. Her younger brother, Doctor of the National Academy Hoejongg, came bearing frost and snow to request an epitaph. Moved by his grief, I could not refuse. Thus I record her lineage and descendants, and append this epitaph.

    The lady was born of the Choi clan of Gokcheok. Her great-grandfather was Master Kyungdeokjae, posthumously named Chi, who during the rebellion of the Sambielyochoae fled to hiding among fishermen without compromise. Her grandfather was Yebinseung Tongjeong, posthumously named Sinmok, who lived in reclusion and was known as a man of virtue. Her father was the scholar Jinsa, posthumously named Youngsue, who gained renown for his poetry but died young. Her maternal grandfather was Pajun Baekgun of Jugyesa, posthumously named Jongyeon, known for his integrity and love of the people.

    She bore sons and daughters. The Director of Ceremonies married the daughter of Right Minister Kang Changsoo and had one daughter; he took as his second wife the daughter of Minister Paku Gyung and had one son named Hwe. The Academy Doctor married the daughter of Judge Jeong Injeon and had two sons named Kang and Ha, both still young.

    *The Epitaph:*

    As a daughter, she held fast to virtue,
    As a bride, she walked the path of propriety.
    As a mother, she bore herself with grace—
    Never did that grace falter or fail.
    Justly did she bear worthy sons,
    Whom honor and office came to bless.
    In life she served Munjong well,
    In death she rests beside his grave.
    Where mountain peaks entwine and waters flow long,
    Lies this true abode of the spirits,
    May this stone endure without error,
    Preserving her memory for endless ages.
  footnotes:
    - Yuljung (栗亭) was a place name associated with the Yun family.
    - The three ministries refer to the Secretariat, Chancellery, and Department of State Affairs of the Goryeo administrative system.
    - The Eulsa examination (을사년 과거) refers to the civil service examination held in 1465.
    - Sambielyochoae (三別抄) was a resistance movement in thirteenth-century Goryeo.
    - The Hongwu reign (洪武) refers to the early Ming Dynasty period (1368-1398).
